Writing papers is hard. But one of my favourite parts of them is creating nice figures. There's a deep satisfaction in creating a figure that simply displays the message you want. But you also do need to write captions. Sometimes I felt like my figures were strong enough that they needed very little in the captions But during my postdoc at Monash, my supervisor, [Professor Di Cook](https://www.dicook.org/),  gave me advice for how to write captions in a meeting, and it has stuck with me. The advice is now in the [proof reading checklists](https://journal.r-project.org/share/proofreading-checklist.pdf) for the [R Journal](https://journal.r-project.org/).

Again, I am not taking credit for this, but I just wanted to put this out there because I think it should be shared more widely.

Captions should have three components:

1. What is the plot/table about,
2. Specific details of plot/table, like what type of display and how variables are mapped, 
3. The most important thing that the reader should learn.

